            <fr:addr type="user">holomorphic</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>holomorphic.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Holomorphic">Holomorphic</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>25</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A continuous function "in every direction"</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Is a very strong condition</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>From <fr:link type="local" href="Cauchy's%20Integral%20theorem.xml" addr="Cauchy's Integral theorem" title="Cauchy's Integral theorem">Cauchy's Integral theorem</fr:link> we know that the integral of a holomorphic function over the boundary any simply connected domain is zero. This gives rise to the <fr:link type="local" href="Cauchy's%20Integral%20Formula.xml" addr="Cauchy's Integral Formula" title="Cauchy's Integral Formula">Cauchy's Integral Formula</fr:link>, hence proves that</fr:li>
<fr:li>A holomorphic function is automatically <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^\infty ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="Morera's%20Theorem.xml" addr="Morera's Theorem" title="Morera's Theorem">Morera's Theorem</fr:link> gives a strong condition to test for "holomorphicity"</fr:li>
<fr:li>An <fr:link type="external" href="analytic">analytic</fr:link> complex-valued function is <fr:strong>automatically</fr:strong> holomorphic and vice versa <fr:ul><fr:li>This is <fr:em>not true for real functions!</fr:em></fr:li> <fr:li>Oftentimes "<fr:link type="external" href="analytic">analytic</fr:link>" and "holomorphic" are used interchangably</fr:li></fr:ul> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\longrightarrow ]]></fr:tex> simple differentiability implies such a strong property like being representable by a power series!</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
